WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.930 --> 00:00:07.180
Kevin Connolly: But… the… In the spirit of thinking about how to…

2
00:00:07.370 --> 00:00:16.779
Kevin Connolly: land a job, and get a job, it's really about that judgment that occurs at the top of funnel, from the kind of perspective. Is your resume sufficient,

3
00:00:16.820 --> 00:00:33.650
Kevin Connolly: this screening thing that I mentioned is kind of a challenge, like, people using AI in the interview process, recruiting teams want. There's a little bit of a philosophy debate here, where some teams are very forward when they say, like, please use AI in our interview process. You will use it as an employee, so you can use it during the interview.

4
00:00:33.650 --> 00:00:40.279
Kevin Connolly: just, like, let us know. And I actually want to judge how you use AI as a tool. And then other teams that'll say.

5
00:00:40.589 --> 00:00:48.280
Kevin Connolly: We know you will use AI here, but we want to get, like, the raw version of you. Do not use it at all. It's a verbal and you'll be judged.

6
00:00:48.569 --> 00:00:51.589
Kevin Connolly: And there's different styles, there.

7
00:00:51.599 --> 00:01:05.859
Sathya Narayanan: I don't know if there's an answer to this question, I apologize. Do you have a sense of the percentage, like, even at a ballpark, are you seeing a trend on that? Is more moving in the direction of, kind of, allowing AI versus not? Can you say…

8
00:01:05.860 --> 00:01:06.180
Kevin Connolly: Absolutely.

9
00:01:06.180 --> 00:01:07.539
Sathya Narayanan: What kind of qualitative, yeah.

10
00:01:07.540 --> 00:01:15.309
Kevin Connolly: Yeah, that's a really… I wish I had that number, but I do not. I think if I were to try and analyze it in our data, I might…

11
00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:25.260
Kevin Connolly: I, you know, because it would… basically, it would be on the job posting and, like, a free-form text description, like, you are or are not asked to, so we'd have to do, like, a…

12
00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:43.640
Kevin Connolly: some analysis of job postings along those lines, but it might be kind of fuzzy. It's a nice idea, but I don't… I don't have an answer offhand. It's mostly from my in-person sort of anecdotal discussion with recruiting teams, where we say this, and they're like, yeah, we're, like, talking about that a lot, you know, or we're not really sure. Some people are just like, we let them use AI all the time.

13
00:01:43.690 --> 00:01:46.750
Kevin Connolly: So it's… it's strictly anecdotal at this point, but I do think it's…

14
00:01:46.870 --> 00:01:51.489
Kevin Connolly: I'd be very confident in saying that, like, people are discussing this, like, as a consideration.

15
00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:53.869
Sathya Narayanan: Is it… is it true that more…

16
00:01:54.060 --> 00:02:01.959
Sathya Narayanan: AA fluency requirements are getting into the job description, or even that is not… I've read kind of places, yeah, people say.

17
00:02:01.960 --> 00:02:12.299
Kevin Connolly: Yeah, I should have… I should have put that… we have… one of the Talent Trend blog posts does… does, an analysis of, the rise of AI

18
00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:24.270
Kevin Connolly: related, skills and descriptions in the job posting body and the job posting title. So we, like, break it out two ways to see, like, is AI starting to creep into the titles of roles themselves?

19
00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:34.029
Kevin Connolly: And I don't recall the percentages change, offhand, but it is, you know, a traditional, like, up and to the right sort of creeping chart.

20
00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:35.400
Jeff D'Andria: I have a question.

